The White House Office of the Press Secretary held a daily briefing on April 30, 2015. The briefing covered a range of topics including the nomination of Gayle Smith to be the next Administrator of the U.S. Agency for International Development, the President's meeting with the New Democrat Coalition, and the ongoing negotiations on trade promotion authority and the Trans-Pacific Partnership agreement. The briefing also addressed the Military Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission's recommendations, the defense authorization bill, and the Clinton Foundation's disclosure of foreign donors. Additionally, the briefing touched on the fall of Saigon and its relevance to the President's foreign policy agenda, as well as the President's recent comments on racial tension in America.